<paragraph id="1F0B3690FFC7FF96658410F1D21E21F6" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="2DC0EA82FFC7FF96658410F1D33A218E" bold="true" box="[199,526,1924,1949]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Ergatoid Queen. Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This caste is diagnosed by: (1) ergatoid, with small ocelli on head, (2) in profile, petiolar node rounded, (3) inferior propodeal spines wider than high, apex broadly rounded, and (4) first gastral tergum smooth and polished, strongly shining (
<figureCitation id="878F2A15FFC7FF9667EB10B9D22E21F6" box="[680,794,1996,2021]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="45.[151,249,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[412,1170,193,1955]" captionTargetId="figure@45.[412,1175,193,1956]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURE 19. Photograph of Pogonomyrmex cunicularius Mayr ergatoid queen: (A) frontal view of head, (B) lateral view of body, and (C) dorsal view of body (CASENT 0173109). Photographs by April Nobile from www. AntWeb. org." pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="2DC0EA82FFC7FF9667EB10B9D22E21F6" bold="true" box="[680,794,1996,2021]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Figure 19</emphasis>
</figureCitation>
).
